{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Branch staleness detection correctly identifies branches with commits not in main, older than the configured age threshold, and no open PR.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Real failure risk is at the git-history/age computation boundary with actual branch state, which commonly depends on real git subprocess behavior and commit metadata handling. I considered Integration, but rejected it because this behavior’s failure artifact is environment-dependent git state evaluation (not just pure module handoff). No LLM dependency and no multi-agent chain.","test_description":"Create a real temporary git repo, make `main` and a feature branch with old commits not reachable from `main`, ensure no PR record for that branch, run staleness detection end-to-end, and assert it is flagged stale only when age threshold is exceeded.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.06,"Integration":0.35,"System":0.55,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Session-start setup emits a stale-work warning with actionable branch context when the current branch is stale.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior is mainly module wiring: startup flow consumes computed branch state and emits a warning payload/message. Integration is enough to catch real failures in handoff/formatting. I considered System, but rejected it because the behavior text does not require real OS/session bootstrap mechanics; an in-process startup entrypoint test can reproduce the failure. No AI output dependency.","test_description":"Wire startup setup with a stubbed stale-branch state provider and assert emitted warning includes branch name, age/context, and action guidance when current branch is stale.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.2,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"A local status-classifier function maps computed branch state to labels (`clean`, `stale-no-pr`) deterministically.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is a single deterministic mapping function with no I/O boundary. Failure is local logic only. Higher levels are unnecessary because no module interaction, OS/network/subprocess, or AI dependency is described.","test_description":"Table-drive inputs for computed branch states and assert exact label outputs (`clean`, `stale-no-pr`) and deterministic repeatability across runs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.005,"Workflow":0.005}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"`/kaizen-wip` against live repo and PR state distinguishes \"clean\" from \"has commits but no PR (STALE)\" in rendered output.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires live repo and PR state, so real infrastructure boundaries (git/CLI and real API or equivalent live service interaction) are in scope. Mocking would likely hide real failures in state retrieval/rendered classification coupling. No LLM quality dependency.","test_description":"Run `/kaizen-wip` in a real repository context with real PR state available, verify rendered output is `clean` for fully merged/no-stale branch and `STALE` for branch with unPR’d commits beyond threshold.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Branches with open or merged PRs are not flagged as stale-no-PR false positives.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Core failure is local contract/state mismatch: detector must correctly combine branch divergence/age with PR status categories (`open`, `merged`). This can be caught by wiring detector + PR-state adapter with realistic fixtures. I considered System, but rejected it because the behavior text does not require live API/network; deterministic PR-state fixtures can expose the false-positive bug. No AI dependency.","test_description":"Integrate branch-state evaluator with PR-status provider fixtures for `open`, `merged`, and `none`, and assert only `none` can produce `stale-no-pr` while `open`/`merged` never do.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.07,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Staleness detection remains correct across rebases or squash merges where commit hashes change but branch state should no longer be classified as unPRed stale work.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Rebase/squash semantics are git-history rewrite behaviors that are easiest to miss with mocks and are tightly tied to real git commit graph/subprocess behavior. Integration fakes often hide these edge cases. No AI output dependency and no multi-agent chain.","test_description":"In a real temporary git repo, create a branch, rebase and squash-merge scenarios that rewrite hashes, then run staleness detection and assert branch is not classified as stale-no-pr once work is effectively integrated.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
